@wagemann_adopted
on-arrival: wagemann_plan_active = 1; economic_plan = 6; budget -= 4; unemployed -= 5; economic_growth += 0.25; workers_spd += 5*(1-dissent); new_middle_spd += 4*(1-dissent); old_middle_spd += 4*(1-dissent); unemployed_spd += 6*(1-dissent); left_dissent += 10; dnvp_relation += 8; nationalism += 2; pro_republic += 2; fiscal_stance -= 0.20; demand_impulse += 0.25; supply_impulse += 0.20; price_pressure += 0.08;

The Wagemann Plan is adopted! Whether through coalition agreement or presidential decree, Germany commits to massive stimulus spending.

The scale is breathtaking: 2 billion marks flowing into the economy. Construction sites open across Germany. Canals are dug, roads paved, electrical grids extended. Employment surges.

The economy responds dramatically. Unemployment falls rapidly. Production rises. The Depression's grip weakens.

Our left wing is conflicted: "Why does a conservative plan get implemented when our WTB-Plan was rejected? Are we only allowed interventionist economics when right-wingers propose it?"

But our working-class base benefits tangibly. Jobs return. Wages stabilize. The SPD gets some credit for supporting the program, though conservative nationalists claim the glory.

[? if dnvp_relation >= 40 : The DNVP uses economic recovery to rebuild support, claiming credit for "national economic mobilization." ?]

The bitter lesson: Germany would accept massive stimulus when framed as nationalist mobilization, but not when proposed as socialist economics. The same medicine, different packaging.

@wagemann_blocked
on-arrival: wagemann_rejected = 1; crisis_urgency += 2;

Despite our support, the Wagemann Plan is rejected. [? if spd_in_government = 1 : The coalition cannot agree on such massive spending. ?] [? if spd_toleration = 1 : The government lacks sufficient support. ?] Fiscal conservatives in the Center Party ally with reluctant DVP members to block it.

"Germany cannot afford such financial adventures," they declare—the same argument used against the WTB-Plan.

We've now supported two major stimulus proposals—one from the left (WTB), one from the right (Wagemann)—and both were rejected. The message is clear: Germany's establishment prefers Depression to intervention, regardless of ideological source.

[? if crisis_urgency >= 7 : How long can paralysis continue as unemployment soars and extremists gain? ?]

